Notes
Supplier Onboarding and Engagement
The meeting clarified that the supplier onboarding process must include a structured evaluation and continuous engagement through a dedicated app interface to build long-term supplier relationships.

The Sri Chakra Supplier Management Program (SSMP) was defined by Vijaya Raghava Swaroop Kongara as encompassing initial onboarding via a 28-question evaluation, followed by improvement plans and ongoing training programs delivered through the app (17:02)

The onboarding questionnaire qualifies suppliers and identifies areas for improvement, which then trigger customized improvement plans.
Both supplier and field executive sign off on evaluation and improvement interactions to create an auditable trail.
Training modules include health, safety, digital literacy, and PPE usage, with impact assessments collected via simple surveys post-training.
This engagement builds supplier loyalty and ensures compliance before the supplier enters transactional business.
Krishna Mohan Adusumilli emphasized the need for the SSMP app to support program management tools for administrators to create, publish, and track improvement plans and audits to closure (24:33)

Audit schedules should be calendar-driven and apply to all suppliers based on maturity with sign-offs at both ends.
Account managers will anchor training programs but audits will be handled by separate internal or external auditors to ensure objectivity.
The app must enable account managers to monitor and update the status of improvement plans and audits in real time.
Supplier traceability requirements were highlighted by Swaroop, who explained the need to track the entire supply chain below the immediate supplier to meet brand requirements on responsible sourcing (29:30)

Suppliers should be able to register their own sub-suppliers, potentially verified by the field team, to build a verified multi-tier traceability network.
This traceability data will be tied to ESG reporting and supply chain transparency initiatives.
An incentive system tied to traceability data input was proposed, rewarding suppliers with points or redeemable benefits to encourage participation (44:04).
The app interface must prioritize simplicity and accessibility as reinforced by Shreyash Jain and Krishna (47:38)

WhatsApp-based interaction with magic links opening detailed views in browsers will avoid app update issues and support multiple device types.
Multilingual support for at least three South Indian languages is critical to accommodate informal and semi-formal suppliers.
The conversational UI will detect and use the supplier’s preferred language automatically to improve engagement fidelity.
Integration with ERP and Data Architecture
The group agreed that the SSMP app should act as an interface layer with ERPNext, avoiding unnecessary data duplication while ensuring real-time access to transactional data and audit trails.

Krishna Mohan Adusumilli clarified that all transactional data such as debit notes, quality reports, ledgers, and payment histories should reside in ERPNext, with the SSMP app fetching and presenting data via APIs on demand (12:05)

The app will store only supplier relationship and engagement data, reducing data redundancy and ERP system bloat.
This separation ensures audit teams can find all transaction records in ERP while maintaining supplier communication in SSMP.
Krishna requested a follow-up technical call to finalize data ownership and storage design due to complexities in multi-tier supplier data (31:20).
Swaroop advocated strongly for housing all supplier data, including tier 3 and 4 suppliers, inside ERPNext to maintain data protection and future scalability as suppliers evolve (33:32)

He proposed tagging suppliers by tiers in ERP and pushing relevant notifications to SSMP for supplier actions.
However, authentication challenges may arise when suppliers update traceability data, requiring careful IT design to ensure seamless verification and data sync.
Both ERP-centric and SSMP-centric models have pros and cons; deeper brainstorming is planned before final decisions (34:56).
Shreyash Jain and Krishna agreed on a hybrid approach where SSMP will hold key supplier data and ERPNext will serve as the master for transactional information, with API-mediated synchronization to balance performance and data integrity (37:00)

They highlighted the need to minimize ERP database bulk while ensuring data consistency and audit compliance.
This architecture supports rapid app responsiveness and reduces backend complexity.
Logistics and Transaction Flows
The group discussed the need to integrate logistics partners and define clear business flows for supplier material deliveries through the SSMP app.

Logistics booking via the app will allow suppliers to schedule vehicle pickup and delivery dates, with clear demarcation of cost responsibility between supplier and Sri Chakra (40:25)

Two models exist: suppliers book and pay for transport or buyers arrange collection at agreed X-Works or delivered pricing.
The app should accommodate negotiated transport prices and enable Sri Chakra to pay transporters directly, deducting costs from supplier payments to ease supplier cash flow issues.
Krishna noted difficulty finding logistics partners with API integration, requesting business contacts for potential partners (38:08).
Sales and procurement transactions will also be integrated into the app, allowing customers to view inventory, prices, and place orders, with sales orders created in ERPNext based on app inputs (51:32)

Logistics processes similar to procurement will apply to sales, including own fleet or customer-arranged transport.
This expands the app’s scope beyond supplier management to a comprehensive supply and sales transaction interface.
Process Improvements and Configuration Flexibility
The need for a configurable, user-manageable system was emphasized to reduce maintenance overhead and improve responsiveness.

Krishna stressed that the SSMP app should allow internal users to configure questionnaires, audits, and training content without developer involvement to avoid operational bottlenecks (56:33)

This self-service portal will enable adding or removing questions and scheduling events quickly.
Shreyash confirmed plans for an admin portal allowing real-time configuration and monitoring of workflows (57:39).
Mandatory data privacy and consent management must be incorporated into the app to comply with recent IT laws, requiring supplier and customer agreement before data collection (55:54)

This ensures legal compliance and protects organizational reputation.
Next Steps and Demonstration Planning
The team agreed on delivering a practical demonstration and further discussions to refine requirements and solution design.

Shreyash Jain offered to prepare a WhatsApp-based demo showcasing multilingual, menu-driven supplier interactions and training workflows to validate user experience and technical feasibility (50:15)

He proposed an in-person visit near Vijayawada on 30th to present the demo and discuss further (51:19).
Krishna and Swaroop welcomed this and agreed to align schedules for the session (58:17).
Further technical calls are planned to finalize the ERP-SSMP integration architecture and logistics API partnerships to ensure a smooth implementation (32:28, 38:03).

Business contacts for logistics API providers will be shared by Swaroop and Shreyash to expedite partner identification (39:10).
The team committed to consolidating meeting points into a formal document capturing requirements, workflows, and design considerations for stakeholder buy-in and development planning (53:43).

